        "content": "<p>Well it might just be a skill issue on my part, the point is that this is not a theorem, this is a computation, and the community have not prioritised writing things like tactics for computations (and I in particular am not really interested in problems which boil down to computations like this so this is why it might be a skill issue, there could be tricks I don't know about). What we're good at is proving theorems in commutative algebra. Another example of something high school kids would understand and Lean would be really bad at right now is the basic circle and triangle theorems, where Lean doesn't graphically display what's going on and the proofs are incredibly detailed; I'm not sure I'd like to tackle basic GCSE problems about angle-chasing right now. On the other hand I think that there is plenty of scope for making stuff like this much easier.  The point is that someone has to do it -- people just moaning about it on Zulip doesn't get it done because right now it's not clear that making this better is anyone's priority and people are typically just working for fun and for free on this stuff.</p>",
        "id": 501625191,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1740423507
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh sorry, I only just noticed your question:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>but is there any hope that someday reasoning about these things will get easy.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There are two different things at stake here:<br>\n1) Is it theoretically possible to make questions like this easy: yes absolutely.<br>\n2) Can we find someone who will invest a lot of their time making the infrastructure which makes questions like this easier: that is much harder.</p>\n<p>If I spot someone bright then my instinct is to encourage them to come and work on proving Fermat's Last Theorem with me, not making this infrastructure.</p>",
        "id": 501625576,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1740423623
    },
