    {
        "content": "<p>I think the last line could use some improvement, there is a non-confluent simp lemma here causing it to get stuck on <code>(Set.Icc 3 10).ncard</code> while <code>(Finset.Icc a b).card</code> has a simp lemma</p>",
        "id": 501630901,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1740425400
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But to answer the question about strategies: the strategy here is quite simple. The set we have is not written in a form where it is easy to compute the size, but it is the image under an injective function of a set with an easy to compute size, and injective functions preserve cardinality. So we pull the set back across the function and then hit it with simp (or at least it would be <code>simp</code> if not for a bad simp lemma which we have to use in reverse)</p>",
        "id": 501631844,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1740425702
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My proof is much longer because I wasted time establishing bijectivity rather than just using injectivity</p>",
        "id": 501632484,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1740425912
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the surjectivity part is still kind of there in the proof that the set is equal to the image of f, but the secret trick here is that the definition of the original set is already extremely close to being the image of function <code>f</code> (the existential quantifier is really just constructing an image), which makes that part a one liner</p>",
